<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-921-972  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 921 972.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  Sept 1989 p30(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>After CAD came CAM. ( CAD/CAM used by heating and ventilationequipment maker F.H. Biddle)(includes a related article on thedevelopment of F.H. Biddle's CAD/CAM network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Palframan, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Nuneaton, England, maker of heating and ventilation equipment F.H.andO;Biddle spent about 150,000 pounds sterling since 1987 on a networkof 35 microcomputers for computer-aided design (CAD),computer-aided manufacturing (CAM), accounting, word processing,data base management and stock control.andP;  An additional250,000-plus pounds sterling was spent on a CNC punching andnibbling machine.andP;  The computers are mostly Tandon PCA 20workstations connected by a Novell network.andP;  The system wasintended to capture the skills and knowledge of long-termemployees and increase efficiency, productivity and sales whilecutting costs.andP;  AutoCAD was selected as the firm's CAD system,while Camtek's Peps was the software package for CAM.andP;  Theimplementation of the packages and some of the problemsencountered are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   F.H. Biddle (automation).andO;Topic:     AutomationCAD-CAMApplicationsHeatingCase StudyManufacturers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>